======================================================================
PART 2: THE UNIT CIRCLE REGIME (x ∈ [-1, 0))
======================================================================

When -1/4 < x < 0: eigenvalues are REAL, both in (-1, 1).
  I(P_k, x) → 0 exponentially.

When x = -1/4: CRITICAL POINT. Double eigenvalue λ = 1/2.
  I(P_k, -1/4) = (k+2) / 2^{k+1}  (linear × exponential decay)

When -1 ≤ x < -1/4: eigenvalues are COMPLEX, on the unit circle!
  |λ±| = √(-x) → I(P_k, x) is PERIODIC/QUASIPERIODIC!
  At x = -1: |λ±| = 1, period = 6.
  At x = -1/2: |λ±| = 1/√2 ≈ 0.707, DECAYING oscillation.

Verification of I(P_k, -1/4) = (k+2)/2^{k+1}:
  k=0: I(P_0, -1/4) = 1.000000, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 1.000000, match=True
  k=1: I(P_1, -1/4) = 0.750000, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.750000, match=True
  k=2: I(P_2, -1/4) = 0.500000, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.500000, match=True
  k=3: I(P_3, -1/4) = 0.312500, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.312500, match=True
  k=4: I(P_4, -1/4) = 0.187500, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.187500, match=True
  k=5: I(P_5, -1/4) = 0.109375, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.109375, match=True
  k=6: I(P_6, -1/4) = 0.062500, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.062500, match=True
  k=7: I(P_7, -1/4) = 0.035156, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.035156, match=True
  k=8: I(P_8, -1/4) = 0.019531, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.019531, match=True
  k=9: I(P_9, -1/4) = 0.010742, (k+2)/2^(k+1) = 0.010742, match=True

======================================================================
PART 3: PHASE DIAGRAM OF I(P_k, x)
======================================================================

Three regimes:
  x < -1/4: OSCILLATORY (complex eigenvalues, period depends on x)
  x = -1/4: CRITICAL (double real eigenvalue)
  x > -1/4: EXPONENTIAL (real eigenvalues, growth for x > 0)

Period structure:
  x = -1: arg = π/3, period = 6
  x = -cos²(π/5) - 1/4 = ?: arg = π/5, period = 10
  x = -cos²(π/4) - 1/4 = ?: arg = π/4, period = 8

Exact x for given period p (arg = π/p for period 2p):
  period   6: x = -1.000000, |λ+| = 1.000000
           verified periodic: True
  period   8: x = -0.500000, |λ+| = 0.707107
           verified periodic: False
  period  10: x = -0.381966, |λ+| = 0.618034
           verified periodic: False
  period  12: x = -0.333333, |λ+| = 0.577350
           verified periodic: False
  period  14: x = -0.307979, |λ+| = 0.554958
           verified periodic: False
  period  16: x = -0.292893, |λ+| = 0.541196
           verified periodic: False
  period  20: x = -0.276393, |λ+| = 0.525731
           verified periodic: False
  period  24: x = -0.267949, |λ+| = 0.517638
           verified periodic: False

======================================================================
PART 4: OBLONG FUGACITIES IN THE PHASE DIAGRAM
======================================================================

Integer-eigenvalue fugacities x = k(k+1) (oblong numbers):
  x = 0: λ = 1, 0  (degenerate)
  x = 2: λ = 2, -1  (tournaments)
  x = 6: λ = 3, -2
  x = 12: λ = 4, -3
  x = 20: λ = 5, -4

These are ALL in the EXPONENTIAL regime (x > -1/4).
The 'tournament fugacity' x=2 is the SMALLEST nonzero oblong.

G_k(n) = I(P_n, k(k+1)) for first few k and n:
  n       x=0       x=2       x=6      x=12      x=20
  0         1         1         1         1         1
  1         1         3         7        13        21
  2         1         5        13        25        41
  3         1        11        55       181       461
  4         1        21       133       481      1281
  5         1        43       463      2653     10501
  6         1        85      1261      8425     36121
  7         1       171      4039     40261    246141
  8         1       341     11605    141361    968561
  9         1       683     35839    624493   5891381

Closed form for I(P_n, k(k+1)):
  k=1 (x=2): I(P_n,2) = 1.3333·2^n + -0.3333·(-1)^n  ✓
  k=2 (x=6): I(P_n,6) = 1.8000·3^n + -0.8000·(-2)^n  ✓
  k=3 (x=12): I(P_n,12) = 2.2857·4^n + -1.2857·(-3)^n  ✓
  k=4 (x=20): I(P_n,20) = 2.7778·5^n + -1.7778·(-4)^n  ✓

======================================================================
PART 5: THE FIBONACCI WORD — 2 AND 3 AS TILE LENGTHS
======================================================================

Fibonacci numbers count tilings of a 1×n strip with tiles of length 1 and 2.
Jacobsthal numbers count tilings where 1-tiles have 1 color and 2-tiles have 2 colors.
At fugacity x: tiles of length 2 have x colors.

Fibonacci word (first 30): abaababaabaababaababaabaababaa
  a count: 19, b count: 11
  ratio a/b: 1.7273 (should → φ = 1.6180)
Tile lengths: [2, 3, 2, 2, 3, 2, 3, 2, 2, 3, 2, 2, 3, 2, 3, 2, 2, 3, 2, 3, 2, 2, 3, 2, 2, 3, 2, 3, 2, 2]
  Running sums: [2, 5, 7, 9, 12, 14, 17, 19, 21, 24, 26, 28, 31, 33, 36]
  Beatty B(φ²): [2, 5, 7, 10, 13, 15, 18, 20, 23, 26, 28, 31, 34, 36, 39]
  Match: False
  Asymptotically: partial_sum(k) ~ k·φ² = k·0.8090

★ INSIGHT: The Fibonacci word with tile lengths 2 and 3:
  2 = tournament fugacity (x in I(Ω,2) = H)
  3 = x+1 = the 'augmented fugacity'
  2+3 = 5 (pentagon), 2×3 = 6 (period)

